# LiVEiT® Clear Space

The LiVEiT® logo should always be surrounded by sufficient clear space to ensure maximum visibility and recognition.

Clear space prevents the logo from competing with surrounding text, graphics and interface elements, helping to preserve the integrity of the LiVEiT® visual identity.

---

# Purpose

Maintaining clear space improves:

* Recognition
* Readability
* Professional presentation
* Brand consistency
* Visual impact

The logo should always remain the primary visual element within its immediate surroundings.

---

# Minimum Clear Space

A minimum exclusion zone must be maintained around every official LiVEiT® logo.

No other visual elements should enter this area.

These include:

* Text
* Images
* Icons
* Buttons
* Borders
* Decorative graphics
* Other logos

The exclusion zone should remain free of visual distractions.

---

# Measuring Clear Space

Clear space should be measured using a consistent reference taken from the official logo artwork.

Unless otherwise specified in future asset documentation, maintain a minimum clear space equal to the height of the capital **"L"** in the LiVEiT® wordmark on all four sides.

This measurement should scale proportionally with the logo.

---

# Digital Applications

For websites and applications:

* Do not position the logo against browser edges.
* Maintain generous spacing within headers.
* Avoid crowding navigation elements.
* Allow sufficient margin when placing the logo inside cards or panels.

Whitespace is an important part of the LiVEiT® design language.

---

# Printed Material

For printed publications:

* Maintain the same proportional exclusion zone.
* Avoid placing the logo close to page edges.
* Leave adequate space between the logo and body text.
* Ensure the logo remains visually prominent.

Print layouts should follow the same principles as digital applications.

---

# Multiple Logos

When displaying the LiVEiT® logo alongside partner or sponsor logos:

* Maintain equal spacing between logos.
* Preserve the LiVEiT® exclusion zone.
* Do not overlap exclusion areas.
* Ensure no logo appears visually dominant through crowding.

Every logo should have sufficient space to remain distinct.

---

# Background Graphics

Decorative elements should not enter the clear space area.

Avoid placing:

* Patterns
* Illustrations
* Photographs
* Gradients
* Interface components

within the exclusion zone surrounding the logo.

---

# Incorrect Usage

The following examples should be avoided:

* Placing text directly beside the logo.
* Positioning the logo against page edges.
* Allowing interface elements to overlap the exclusion zone.
* Placing graphics behind or immediately adjacent to the logo.
* Reducing spacing to fit within a restricted layout.

These practices reduce legibility and weaken brand recognition.

---

# Responsive Layouts

On smaller screens, the clear space should remain proportional.

Reducing the size of the logo does not remove the requirement for adequate surrounding space.

Responsive layouts should prioritise readability over maximising logo size.

---

# Best Practice

When in doubt, allow more space rather than less.

Generous whitespace contributes to the clean, structured and accessible appearance that defines the LiVEiT® Framework.

Maintaining consistent clear space across all applications helps preserve the professionalism and recognisability of the LiVEiT® brand.
